<subSubSection pageId="19" pageNumber="136" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="19.[151,1436,1343,1910]" pageId="19" pageNumber="136">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,1742,1766]" pageId="19" pageNumber="136">Remarks.</emphasis>
This species resembles 
<taxonomicName authority="Sohi &amp; Mann" authorityName="Sohi &amp; Mann" box="[591,896,1742,1766]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Kapsa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="19" pageNumber="136" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="maculata">
<emphasis box="[591,729,1742,1766]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="136">K. maculata</emphasis>
Sohi &amp; 
<collectingCountry box="[828,896,1743,1766]" name="Isle of Man" pageId="19" pageNumber="136">Mann</collectingCountry>
</taxonomicName>
, but the pygofer dorsal appendage is broad and straight, the anal tube appendage is curved caudad, the apex of the paramere is bifurcated, the aedeagal shaft is more slender with a serrated, compressed ventral protrusion, and lacks a ventral process.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="19" pageNumber="136" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="19.[151,1436,1343,1910]" pageId="19" pageNumber="136">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,1850,1874]" pageId="19" pageNumber="136">Etymology.</emphasis>
The specific name is derived from the Latin word “serratus”, referring to serrated edge of aedeagal ventral protrusion.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
